<TEXT>
antiapartheid banners adorn the 
halls at the university of the western cape and the main plaza is 
called freedom square an exile once jailed for terrorism is 
receiving an honorary degree this week 
western cape is the most radical university in south africa its 
chief administrator professor jakes gerwel said when installed as 
rector last year that he plans to preside over an intellectual 
home for the left 
the militance of students and staff contrasts sharply with the 
governments intent in 1960 when it established a college near 
cape town for mixedrace students as part of its segregated 
education system jg miering a white professor who headed the 
school in the 1960s said the white guardian was obliged to 
provide these facilities for his colored mixedrace ward 
the university remains predominantly mixedrace but gerwel is 
determined to increase black enrollment beyond the current 13 
percent his administration is openly committed to preparing 
students for a postapartheid south africa led by the nowvoteless 
black majority 
we are a political thorn in their sides gerwel said of the 
government the establishment doesnt know how to deal with us 
a case in point is the universitys decision to award an 
honorary degree friday to breyten breytenbach a white poet who 
left south africa in 1982 after serving seven years in prison for 
terrorism the government denied breytenbach a visa and a relative 
is to accept the award on his behalf 
at the same graduation ceremony one of the main speakers will 
be cyril ramaphosa general secretary of the militant black 
national union of mineworkers 
last month the universitys governing council elected anglican 
archbishop desmond tutu as chancellor tutu winner of the 1984 
nobel peace prize for his antiapartheid campaigning is the first 
black chosen for the honorary post 
gerwel who as professor of afrikaans literature was a leading 
faculty activist is the second mixedrace rector the first 
richard van der ross led from 197587 and is credited with 
establishing the schools antiapartheid orientation 
most of south africas 3 million mixedrace people live in the 
cape town region the universitys enrollment has soared from 6128 
in 1984 to 11500 this year and multiple construction projects 
cant keep pace with the need for more facilities 
sometimes we cannot teach our students because theres no 
place to put them said owen van den bergh a white who is dean 
of education we have to hope they dont come to class 
the government has cut subsidies to all universities by about 25 
percent this year and adopted regulations to allow further cuts at 
schools that fail to curb campus protest the university of the 
western cape and the predominantly white university of cape town 
successfully challenged the regulations in court but gerwel 
expects the government to try other tactics to tame his school 
one of gerwels priorities is to expand the universitys ties 
with the antiapartheid movement the campus often serves as a 
venue for meetings of militant organizations 
going to uwc is considered by students to be part of the 
political struggle said di bishop vice president of the black 
sash civil rights organization and a university sociology 
researcher youre not going off to an ivory tower for a couple 
of years 
security forces have entered the campus several times in recent 
years to break up protests with tear gas and whips there is 
animosity among some students toward remaining conservative 
professors 
there also is conflict over language some of the 600 teachers 
lecture in english and others in afrikaans the language that many 
mixedrace people have inherited from the mainly dutchdescended 
whites who run the government 
van den bergh forsees increasing tension as black enrollment 
rises he also sees internal pressures building up in individual 
students 
there are a lot who say the right things politically but are 
fundamentally conservative he said they are worried about 
getting a job getting a house 
gerwel said the university could arm itself against 
government pressure by adding more professional schools it now 
offers graduate degrees in law pharmacy and dentistry but he also 
wants the curriculum to accommodate those who have been excluded 
from power and privilege 
in a changed south africa its not going to be a first world 
hightech society he said what is this new south africa we 
are working for were trying to find out the englishlanguage 
universities are geared to capitalism we research alternatives 
although the government provides most of their funds the 
university and the 10 predominantly white universities have almost 
total control of curriculum and campus policies the black 
universities are tightly controlled by the government and 
cooperative administrators and student protests at these schools 
has been repressed 
gerwel said his job keeps one awake at night 
but i wouldnt want to be in any other position were at the 
cutting edge of adjusting to a blackled society 
</TEXT>
