<TEXT>
a person who buys a round for a drinking 
companion may be held liable if the companion gets into an auto 
accident an oregon appeals court ruled wednesday 
the decision involved a suit filed by the red steer bar in 
portland against richard howard whose stepson lonnie d johnson 
got into a accident in 1982 that injured another man 
the bar settled with the injured man james solberg for 
425000 and then sued howard who according to the suit 
accompanied johnson to three bars the two buying drinks for each 
other on the day of the collision 
lawyers for the bar claim howard should be responsible for some 
of the damages because he knew or should have known johnson had a 
drinking problem had been convicted of drunken driving and had 
been in accidents while drinking 
multnomah county circuit judge lee johnson dismissed the 
lawsuit finding noi legal basis for it but the court of appeals 
on wednesday reinstated the case 
the appeals court said howard could be found to owe damages 
under a common law negligence theory that says someone who 
substantially assists or encourages negligent conduct by 
another can be held liable 
the decision is believed the first ruling in oregon to deal with 
liability of a drinking companion at a commercial establishment 
in dismissing the lawsuit the lower court judge said it would 
an unprecedented and unwarranted extension of common law 
liability to hold that howard had a legal duty to solberg 
</TEXT>
