some political observers and aquino supporters have interpreted 
the wording of the transitory provision to mean mrs aquino is not 
bound by the oneterm limit 
in its report amnesty international praised the aquino 
government for some very real progress in human rights 
particularly in restoring legal safeguards and in greatly reducing 
the use of torture 
but it called on the government to reaffirm publicly its 
commitment to protect human rights the report said amnesty 
international knew of no cases where soldiers had been punished for 
human rights violations 
it cited the february 1987 killing of 17 civilians in lupao the 
military said the killings took place after a lieutenant was killed 
by a communist sniper during a patrol in lupao 
with regards to no soldier being convicted in fact charges 
have been filed against the soldiers involved or implicated in the 
lupao massacre mrs aquino said 
we are living in a democracy while it is true there is 
evidence everyone is entitled to due process of law even those 
who are accused should have their day in court 
mary concepcion bautista chairwoman of the commission on human 
rights also criticized the amnesty international report as 
exaggerated 
she said the government was investigating about 200 cases of 
human rights abuse claiming there is a serious effort to clean 
up 
mrs bautista said investigations of human rights abuses against 
the military were often not publicized to avoid demoralizing 
soldiers who are fighting the rebels 
the insurgents dont follow the rules she said soldiers 
complain that when they fight the insurgents they have one hand 
tied behind their back 
last year about 150 police and soldiers were fatally shot on 
manila streets communist rebels claimed responsibility for about 
half the killings 
an average of 10 soldiers civilians or police officers are 
killed daily in clashes between government and rebel forces 
