although the superpower missile treaty 
has not been ratified yet the soviet union is already adjusting 
its nuclear missile force to regain firepower lost through the 
accord natos top commander said 
the commander us gen john r galvin said on wednesday that 
the moves were expected and were not in violation of the treaty 
signed last december to eliminate the superpowers medium and 
shorterrange nuclear missiles worldwide missiles covered by the 
treaty have ranges from 300 to 3000 miles 
they are restructuring their missile force galvin said in 
an interview with the associated press in his spartan office at 
supreme headquarters allied powers europe galvin likened the 
soviet moves to reshaping a wall from which some stones have been 
removed 
i dont want to get too specific but i get some 
indications that the soviets are readjusting the stones on the 
wall he said adding that the western allies would do this too 
galvin added the soviets will retarget other warheads into 
western europe to cover military targets previously assigned to 
the hundreds of ss20 rockets to be dismantled under terms of the 
superpower accord 
he said it was not yet clear how the soviets would accomplish 
this they may have to take warheads that were aimed in 
another direction and aim them toward western europe galvin said 
the net result he said is likely to be that the soviets will 
partially offset the loss of their ss20s which are triplewarhead 
ballistic missiles capable of striking all of western europe 
the overall capabilities of the soviets would still be 
somewhat lower a small amount lower because of the treaty 
galvin said but the adjustments will to some degree cover 
that 
the north atlantic treaty organization also is seeking to adjust 
and modernize its remaining nuclear forces in europe to partially 
compensate for the loss of the us cruise and pershing 2 missiles 
