<TEXT>
some rock climbers at hueco tanks state 
historical park have been gluing stones to the sheer rock walls to 
create handholds and footholds officials say 
the practice has forced a ban on rockclimbing while officials 
survey the damage and decide whether to allow climbers back on the 
rocks parks and wildlife department spokeswoman suzanne carter 
said wednesday 
hueco tanks was created to protect prehistoric rock drawings 
the area attracted people as long as 10000 years ago because of 
the water that collects in huecos or hollows in the granite 
rock formations 
the defaced walls were discovered in midfebruary and the park 
was closed indefinitely on march 1 to technical climbers who use 
ropes bolts and wedges climbers use the equipment at hueco tanks 
because some of the parks climbing routes are among the most 
challenging in north america 
bolts are screwed into stone to secure safety ropes the 
practice is banned at hueco tanks but park workers have struck an 
unofficial truce with climbers if climbers dont drill any more 
bolts the existing bolts wont be removed 
wedges are placed in cracks and also secure safety ropes they 
are supposed to be removable but some climbers apparently have 
been trying to make the wedges permanent 
they put a wedge in a crack then they will glue it into place 
with the epoxy glue if its not secure ms carter said 
even worse she said is evidence that some climbers have glued 
rocks to the rock faces to create handholds a practice that would 
shock most climbers who take pride in using nothing but chalk on 
their hands and softrubbersoled shoes to aid their ascents 
hueco tanks is about 25 miles east of el paso its brown cliffs 
were created after molten rock intruded into overlying limestone 
millions of years ago and the limestone eroded away some of the 
formations rise 150 feet 
</TEXT>
