<DOCNO> AP880310-0074 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
experts testifying about possible causes of 
a continental airliner crash did not rule out disturbance from a 
plane landing on an adjacent runway but said winds could have 
swept away any such effect 
turbulent winds lead to the early demise of vortex said 
james hallock who has studied the air currents caused by plane 
landings for the department of transportation 
hallock testified wednesday during the second day of a national 
transportation safety board hearing into the nov 15 crash of 
continental flight 1713 which killed 28 people and injured 54 at 
denvers stapleton international airport 
george greene of the national aeronautics and space 
administrations langley research center who also has studied 
vortex agreed that winds generally diminish the effect of such 
turbulence 
federal aviation administration officials tried to elicit from 
greene a definite statement on whether vortex caused the stapleton 
crash but ntsb board member joseph t nall chairman of the 
inquiry would not allow him to answer 
nall said conclusions about what caused the crash must be made 
by the ntsb when it completes its investigation a final report is 
not expected until later this year 
continental spokesman bruce hicks said the witnesses testimony 
did not mean vortex should be ruled out as a possible cause 
nobody shot down anything today he said 
earlier wednesday an airplane engineer testified that enough 
snow fell during the 24 minutes that continental 1713 awaited 
takeoff for ice buildup on the wings to have been a possible factor 
in the crash 
continental officials said they believe wing icing can be ruled 
out as a factor because the plane exceeded the speed at which it 
likely would have stalled from ice 
ralph brumby manager of aerodynamics and acoustics for 
mcdonnell douglas corp which manufactured the dc9 said 0032 
inches of precipitation or about onethird of an inch of snow 
fell in the 24 minutes between deicing and takeoff 
if all that snow turned to ice on the wings the dc9 could have 
stalled after takeoff brumby said ice can change the shape of a 
wing affecting lift 
brumby under questioning by continental officials said that 
the amount of precipitation that fell between the time the plane 
was deiced and takeoff was enough to cause the plane to stall at 
about 150 knots or a little more than 170 mph 
but he said it was impossible to draw a definite conclusion that 
ice on the wing was a factor based on the theory that all the snow 
had turned to ice 
there are so many open parameters he said we dont know 
the amount of roughness generated by the water collection 
he also said officials do not know how long the deicing fluid 
was able to prevent buildup before the plane took off 
</TEXT>
