<TEXT>
doctors used a laser in clearing a 
womans clogged coronary artery but cautioned that there was no 
evidence that the beam of energy cleared away the fatty despoits 
we put a fiber down there we gave it energy and we did it 
safely dr leonard nordstrom said wednesday of the procedure 
performed at methodist hospital 
doctors performed the procedure tuesday on a 38yearold woman 
whose right coronary artery was 90 percent clogged 
i dont want to overstate what weve done nordstrom 
stressed at a news conference i think in cases to come well 
have good documentation that we have removed tissue 
nordstrom said he stopped the nonsurgical laser procedure and 
inflated a balloon to enlarge the vessel opening before there was 
evidence that the laser had removed any tissue clogging the artery 
lasers have been used previously during openheart surgery he 
said janis konze said she had no second thoughts about being the 
first patient to undergo the new procedure 
everything went fine said konze who said she first 
experienced heart pain last summer and consulted with a doctor 
about a month ago 
i feel wonderful im anxious to go home konze said before 
her release wednesday i expect to be back to work within a 
week 
in the procedure a speciallydesigned catheter or slender tube 
is inserted into a patients arterial system and guided to a 
position in the coronary artery where a direct beam of laser energy 
is directed at the blockage 
then the catheter is moved forward to position the balloon in 
the newly enlarged opening the physician inflates the balloon and 
spreads the remaining blockage apart to reopen circulation through 
the artery 
the hourlong procedure during which nordstrom used onesecond 
bursts of laser energy for two to three minutes was the first 
coronary application of the system developed by gv medical inc of 
plymouth 
gvs lastac system is the first integrated system that combines 
the use of direct laser energy fiberoptics and balloon angioplasty 
catheters the company said 
the procedure was pioneered on larger leg arteries more than 
130 procedures have been performed on leg arteries since may 1986 
and the system is now in use at 17 sites around the world gv said 
in a statement 
with the leg arteries the initial success rate was better 
than 90 percent with a success percentage rate in the mid 70s on 
keeping the vessels open james grabek gv president and chief 
executive officer told reporters 
the us food and drug administration has given permission for 
10 test coronary procedures to be done nordstrom said findings 
from these clinical studies will be reviewed by the fda before 
approval is granted for additional procedures or for procedures to 
be done at other sites he said 
