<TEXT>
the us geological survey has sharply reduced 
its estimates of how much oil and gas remain to be found in the 
united states 
the new figures were provided to scientists at a meeting in 
denver last week while a detailed analysis is expected to be made 
public sometime next month explained ozzie girard the surveys 
deputy assistant director for engineering geology 
the survey now estimates reserves of undiscovered crude oil at 
334 billion barrels well below the 546 billion estimated in a 
1981 study 
in addition the agency has lowered its estimates of the 
nations reserves of undiscovered natural gas at 254 trillion cubic 
feet down from the previous estimate of 4268 trillion 
girard said today that the figures issued in denver were 
preliminary and the survey is preparing reports that will detail 
its findings by region and will also explain the methods used to 
arrive at the nunber and the assumptions made by the scientists 
involved 
the new figures termed working papers by girard are based on a 
twoyear study looking at drilling results in the last few years 
there are two main reasons for the lower estimates one of 
course is that some previously undiscovered oil and gas fields 
have now been found 
in addition however unsuccessful drilling efforts in some 
areas that had been thought to be promising have caused scientists 
to lower their expectations for new finds officials said 
