<TEXT>
thousands of police patrolled the tibetan 
capital of lhasa on foot and in trucks today on the anniversary of 
a bloody uprising foreigners in lhasa said hundreds of people were 
arrested in the past six days 
the anniversary of the outbreak of the 1959 tibetan uprising 
against chinese rule passed without major incident said foreigners 
in lhasa contacted by telephone from the southwest china city of 
chengdu 
but more than 100 trucks carrying armed police drove through the 
main streets of the city of 150000 in a show of force and several 
dozen police with machine guns stood in front of the citys holiest 
buddhist temple the jokhang said benjamin watson of new york 
city a tourist 
watson who speaks tibetan said tibetans estimated at least 300 
people had been arrested since a clash saturday between police and 
tibetans demanding independence up to eight people were reported 
killed in the clashes 
the official news agency xinhua also said the situation in lhasa 
today was normal it said 100 top tibetans gathered in lhasa to 
denounce the riots and those who conduct evil doings under the 
guise of lama monks 
another foreign traveler in lhasa who said she spoke some 
tibetan said tibetans had told her of a police sweep today on the 
jokhang temple in which monks were arrested she spoke on condition 
of anonymity 
she said armed police were stationed at every corner of the 
barkhor market square around the jokhang and there was no 
recurrence of saturdays daylong battle between police and monkled 
tibetans 
march 10 is the 29th anniversary of a tibetan revolt against 
chinese rule that resulted in the flight of the dalai lama 
spiritual leader of the tibetans and 100000 followers and a 
bloody crackdown by the chinese army 
a nepalesetibetan interviewed today in the southwestern china 
city of chengdu air gateway to lhasa said he had seen signs in 
lhasa written in tibetan and posted before saturdays disturbance 
calling for people to rise up on march 10 
on that day in 1959 thousands of tibetans surrounded the 
norbulinka the dalai lamas summer palace in lhasa after hearing 
rumors that their godking would be kidnapped by the chinese army 
on march 17 the dalai lama fled from the palace and led his 
followers to exile in india on march 20 the army attacked the 
palace and quashed the rebellion after three days of bloody 
fighting 
in new delhi today about 200 tibetan refugees clashed with 
police during a rally marking the anniversary of the abortive 
uprising seven tibetans and nine policemen were injured 
in a statement issued from his home in exile in dharamsala 
northern india the dalai lama called on tibetans to honor the 
courage of our brethren in tibet who have taken to the streets to 
draw attention to their suffering under chinese colonial rule 
china which took control of tibet in 1950 claims the mountain 
region has been part of chinese territory for seven centuries many 
tibetans disagree and hold deep antagonisms toward the chinese 
because of the communist governments past suppression of tibetan 
language customs and religion 
tibetans led by monks from lhasas main monasteries staged 
three proindependence demonstrations last september and october 
including a violent clash on oct 1 in which at least 14 died 
after those disturbances chinese authorities closed off some 
monasteries and subjected monks to reeducation campaigns 
there were no other major shows of resistance and authorities 
decided to go ahead with the annual 10day moinlam qenmo prayer 
festival one of tibetan buddhisms most important events 
the disturbances saturday began on the final day of the 
festival when monks stood up at the jokhang temple began shouting 
proindependence and prodalai lama slogans and throwing rocks at 
police 
except for sporadic rockthrowing incidents on sunday lhasa has 
reportedly been calm since saturday 
