<TEXT>
us surgeon general c everett koop said today he 
supports trying out a needleexchange program for drug addicts in 
the united states to slow the spread of aids 
while stressing that he was not proposing such a plan but rather 
supporting others who call for it koop said drug abuse was the 
likeliest way aids or aquired immune deficiency syndrome could 
spread through the heterosexual population 
i think we should have a pilot program in the united states 
he said in an interview during the first international conference 
on the global impact of aids about 1000 health specialists from 
63 countries are attending the threeday meeting which opened 
monday at londons barbican center 
under needleexchange programs in europe drug addicts can turn 
in used needles for new ones reducing the risk of contracting aids 
from contaminated drug equipment 
koop acknowledged that many people object to such schemes as 
abetting illegal drug abuse we have to decide whether or not the 
risk of aids from needlesharing is great enough to satisfy that 
objection he said 
if needle exchange could contain the epidemic nobody should 
be against it koop said 
he said pilot projects should be conducted in more than one city 
and mentioned as possibilities new york and los angeles he said a 
nationwide program shouldnt be considered until results of pilot 
programs in the united states and other countries are studied 
a pilot project is proposed for new york but koop criticized it 
for using volunteer methadone users methadone is a substitute used 
to wean addicts off heroin and the volunteers having made the 
commitment to quit drugs should not be exposed again to using 
needles he said 
also wednesday dr manuel carballo chief of social and 
behavioral researcher for the world health organizations global 
program on aids outlined the organizations strategy for slowing 
the spread of the disease dr jonathan mann director of the who 
program was to have given the speech but was unable to attend the 
final days session 
discussion focused on how to reconcile control of the disease 
with individual freedom and on international and national policy on 
aids and its prevention 
a 33nation gallup international survey on attitudes toward aids 
presented to the conference wednesday said that 47 percent of 
respondents in the united states favor testing the entire 
population for aids 
koop said he was totally opposed to mandatory screening 
arguing that only a tiny fraction of the population behaved in a 
way that courted risk 
apart from north america some parts of south america and some 
asian countries concern among individuals about contracting aids 
is relatively low the survey found 
as far as becoming an epidemic was concerned throughout the 
world there was a clear realization that this was likely to occur 
in the case of homosexuals hemophiliacs intravenous drug users 
and promiscuous people the survey says 
in terms of the risk of catching the disease most of the 
peoples of the world were aware of the clear situations in which it 
could be caught it added 
but the survey says substantial minorities in many parts of the 
world do not understand how the disease is transmitted and said 
they would refuse to work with a person carrying the aids virus 
there is a fear that one can get aids by means which are not 
supported by scientific practice for instance sharing a drinking 
glass or via insect bites other perceived risks such as 
coughs and sneezes friendly kissing appear to be 
identified 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that 
damages the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible to 
infections and cancer it is spread through sexual contact needles 
or syringes shared by drug users infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
