the soviet union is continuing to ship arms to 
nicaragua at a fast pace despite efforts by the usbacked contra 
guerrillas and sandinista government to negotiate a peace accord 
the pentagon said thursday 
during the first two months of 1988 the nicaraguans received 
3100 metric tons or 3400 regular tons of weaponry and war 
materiel worth an estimated 100 million the pentagon said 
the equipment was delivered in 10 arms shipments in january and 
february the defense department said 
if that pace is sustained the nicaraguans will receive at least 
18600 metric tons of weaponry this calendar year compared with an 
estimated 21700 metric tons delivered in 1987 
last years arms deliveries to nicaragua were valued by the 
pentagon at 505 million and arrived in 62 shipments 
the januaryfebruary estimates are contained in an unclassified 
assessment of the nicaraguan military buildup that is updated 
periodically by the defense department for administration leaders 
it was released on request by the pentagons public affairs office 
including the latest estimates the pentagon maintains the 
nicaraguan government has received arms valued at more than 24 
billion since calendar year 1980 
the new update was prepared at a time when president reagan is 
working with lawmakers to fashion an aid program for the contra 
guerrillas us aid to the contras was cut off feb 29 after the 
house refused to endorse an administration plan for military and 
humanitarian aid and then rejected a democratic alternative to 
provide just humanitarian aid 
it also comes during a period of rising doubt about the future 
of peace negotiations nicaraguan leader daniel ortega has 
dismissed roman catholic cardinal miguel obando y bravo as a 
mediator in the talks and the contras have said they need more 
time to consider some of the sandinista proposals 
