<TEXT>
the federal government needs to step up its 
supervision of clinical laboratories in order to end widespread 
fraud and cut the rate of dangerous and sometimes fatal 
misdiagnoses congress was told thursday 
fraud gross overcharging kickbacks and poor quality of care 
are rampant in this industry and federal oversight has been 
nonexistent said rep john dingell dmich chairman of the 
house energy and commerce subcommittee on oversight and 
investigations 
dingell said there is a pervasive pattern of highly 
questionable financial arrangements between laboratories and 
doctors with lab inducements ranging from cash discounts and 
frequent flyer mileage to paying the salaries of doctors aides 
some witnesses cited 20 percent to 40 percent error rates in pap 
tests which detect cervical cancer in women as an example of the 
dangers in unregulated lab procedures 
shirley greening representing the american society for 
cytotechnology said labs have adopted a paps for profit 
mentality under which technicians salaries have stagnated while 
their workloads have increased to dangerous levels 
some cytotechs screen 200 to 300 slides a day or more this 
means looking at one pap smear slide every one and a half 
minutes she said screening at this highproduction pace 
produces fatigue and leads to careless errors 
other problems include piecework pay systems that encourage 
production at the expense of careful diagnosis she said and 
considerable pressure to accept inadequate specimens and call 
them negative so doctors wont send their business to another lab 
greening and others recommended mandatory proficiency testing 
for all diagnostic lab technicians workload limits more federal 
money to monitor labs through the medicare and medicaid programs 
and required public disclosure of lab caseload volume staffing 
fees quality control methods and results 
massachusetts attorney general james shannon said one lab was 
billing the state medicaid program 14 for a complete blood 
chemistry test after the investigation he said the price dropped 
to 230 
investigators have recovered 15 million through settlements 
shannon said and massachusetts medicaid is expected to save up to 
700000 a year due to the lower prices 
shannon said such billing practices were a nationwide problem 
dingell cited several federal investigations including one 
still in progress which have found fraud and kickbacks involving 
hundreds of doctors and millions of dollars in southern california 
philadelphia and elsewhere 
he said the profession has become so lucrative that a 
convicted bank robber is now involved in the operation of one 
southwest lab who has exclaimed you can make more money in the 
operation of clinical labs than you can from robbing banks 
there are about 12000 federally regulated labs in the country 
about 6700 located in hospitals several hundred thousand 
facilities are not federally regulated many of them in physicians 
offices 
dingell said the market for clinical lab testing is estimated at 
20 billion a year and 40 percent of that is federally funded 
through medicare and medicaid 
he said representatives of the lab industry would be heard from 
at a later date 
