<TEXT>
a long and often acrimonious battle 
between north carolina and tennessee over discharges from a 
champion international paper mill ended with approval of a 
compromise but environmentalists said their fight may not be over 
the mill in canton nc produces raw paper stock for milk and 
juice cartons and envelopes and discharges wastes into the pigeon 
river residents downstream in tennessee had complained for years 
that the wastes stained the pigeon dark brown killing game fish 
and reducing the potential for recreational revenues 
tennessee officials agreed wednesday to grant champion a 
variance on its water quality standards the compromise will allow 
the mill to continue operating by forcing it to cut its discharges 
significantly 
this has been hanging over our heads for about three years 
oliver blackwell manager of the mill 
we still have a lot of work to do he said noting that it 
could take months before a revised wastewater discharge permit can 
be issued by the epa this is a big step but we recognize we 
dont have the permit yet 
environmentalists pledged to keep an eye on the plant nelson 
ross one of the founders of the dead pigeon river council in 
tennessee called the agreement only an intermediate step toward 
cleaning up the river 
were going to construct picnic areas ramps for whitewater 
enthusiasts said ross were going to develop some parks along 
the shores of the pigeon river and heaven help champion if they 
dont follow through and clean up the river like theyve pledged to 
do 
in accepting this revised permit champion has agreed to 
operate under the most stringent environmental limits of any mill 
in north america and possibly the world said blackwell its 
going to be difficult but im encouraged 
the canton plant employs about 2300 people with an annual 
payroll of about 73 million an additional 8000 jobs depend on 
champions purchases and contracts 
the compromise drew praise from north carolina gov jim martin 
and tennessee gov ned mcwherter who have been directly involved 
in the negotiations 
this is the first agreement reached to clean up the pigeon 
river in the 80 years since the paper mill began operations said 
mcwherter it is a significant breakthrough in improving the 
rivers quality and allowing us to develop the areas economic 
potential 
the two states werent so complimentary in recent years 
in 1983 tennessee sued champion and the north carolina 
environmental management commission contending the discharge made 
the river unsuitable for fishing swimming boating or drinking 
when north carolina granted champion a new permit in 1985 to 
dump wastewater into the pigeon which begins south of canton and 
flows into cocke county tenn it placed no limit on the color of 
the discharge at tennessees urging the environmental protection 
agency canceled the permit and took juristiction 
the epas first proposed permit said the river could be no 
darker than 50 color units about the color of ginger ale when 
it reached the tennessee border about 60 miles north of the paper 
mill 
enviromentalists have said the color level in the river in cocke 
county ranged from 600 to 800 units 
the proposed fiveyear permit which must be approved by both 
states calls for a reduction in the color discharged from the mill 
by 50 percent with additional reductions when river levels are low 
the compromise calls for tennessee to grant champion a variance 
from the 50unit standard the revised permit allows about twice 
that 
champion already has applied for a variance from north carolina 
which must be approved before the wastewater permit is granted by 
the epa 
blackwell said the modernization of the plant and environmental 
control equipment to comply with the new standards within the 
required threeyear time frame would cost the company about 100 
million 
</TEXT>
