<TEXT>
nine years ago federal health officials set nine 
goals for reducing fatalities from injuries in the united states by 
1990 thursday officials predicted at least six of those goals 
will be met 
the fatality rates from many types of injuries such as car 
accidents house fires and drownings have dropped since 1979 
when the us department of health and human services announced its 
1990 goals the centers for disease control reported thursday 
but in some cases the rates have not fallen as far as the 
government had hoped the cdc said while authorities expect to 
meet the goals on reducing deaths from car crashes childhood 
household accidents house fires and gun accidents the goals for 
reducing deaths from falls and drownings wont be met 
achieving the 1990 objectives will require the coordinated 
efforts of federal state and local agencies academic 
institutions professional associations and private entities the 
atlantabased cdc said in its weekly report 
here from the cdc report are the nations 1990 goals for 
reducing deaths from injuries and the progress being made 
reducing the nations annual motor vehicle fatality rate from 
236 such deaths per 100000 americans in 1978 to 18 per 100000 in 
1990 by 1984 the rate had fallen to 196 and the goal is 
projected to be met in part because of a reduction in 
alcoholrelated fatalities 
reducing the motor vehicle fatality rate for children under 
15 from 9 per 100000 in 1978 to 55 by 1984 the rate had fallen 
to 66 and the goal is projected to be met 
reducing the death rate from falls from 62 per 100000 in 
1978 to 20 the rate had fallen only to 51 by 1984 and the goal 
is not expected to be reached people over 65 continue to have high 
death rates from falls for example in 1984 102 such deaths per 
100000 people age 6574 and 147 per 100000 people over 84 
reducing the death rate for children under 15 in home injuries 
from 6 per 100000 in 1978 to 5 the 1984 rate was 49 already 
meeting the objective 
reducing the drowning rate from 32 per 100000 in 1978 to 
15 the rate had fallen only to 23 in 84 and the goal is not 
expected to be met 
reducing the number of deaths in residential fires from 5401 
in 1978 to 4500 the objective was reached in 1984 when 4466 
americans died in such fires 
reducing the number of deaths in firearm accidents from 1806 
in 1978 to 1700 the goal was met in 1984 when 1668 such deaths 
were reported 
reducing the suicide rate among 1524yearolds from 121 per 
100000 in 1978 to 11 the rate is going up not down it was 122 
per 100000 in 1984 up slightly from 1978 and up about 200 percent 
from 1950 the cdc noted that various suicide prevention approaches 
have been tried in communities but the effectiveness is not known 
reducing the homicide rate among black males aged 1524 from 
707 per 100000 in 1978 to 60 this goal will probably be met 
according to cdc researcher dr richard sattin the rate had fallen 
in 1984 to 615 this goal was set recognizing the high homicide 
rate among young black men sattin said noting that the national 
homicide rate in 1984 was 84 per 100000 americans 
