residents of this sprawling military 
base and neighboring towns mourned again thursday for victims of an 
army aviation accident this time 17 soldiers killed in a 
helicopter collision 
the members of the elite 101st airborne division died tuesday 
when helicopters on separate night training missions slammed into 
each other 
the crash was the worst in fort campbell history and the worst 
army aviation accident since 248 fort campbell soldiers died dec 
12 1985 when a chartered jet bringing them home for christmas 
from a mideast peacekeeping mission crashed in canada 
i think any soldier will tell you that when you fly as many 
hours as they do and perform the exercises they do you can expect 
things to happen said charlie c gentry a motel owner in 
clarksville tenn the closest town to fort campbell 
even so he said to me its kind of like hearing about maybe 
a real close friend i had in high school and hadnt seen for a 
while getting killed in a car wreck so even though i didnt know 
them theres more of a feeling of loss than with other news 
stories 
army crash investigators listened to air traffic control tapes 
and interviewed witnesses in an effort to learn the cause of the 
accident spokesmen said specifics would not be released until a 
full report was made probably within 90 days but said some 
details emerged from talks with air controllers and witnesses 
one of the helicopters was leading a formation of three uh60 
black hawks headed east at an altitude of about 250 feet toward the 
airfield investigators said the lead aircraft was struck 
broadside by another black hawk that was flying alone about six 
miles from the airfield the remaining two aircraft were not 
damaged and landed safely 
the formation of three helicopters was returning infantry troops 
from a livefire exercise said fort campbell spokesman maj randy 
j schoel aircraft flying over the reservation under visual flight 
rules as the four copters were are not generally tracked by 
control tower radar and are responsible for avoiding each other 
schoel said 
the pilots were wearing night vision goggles that amplify 
available light and were supposed to have been in radio contact 
with the forts control tower the army spokesman said 
generally the helicopters running lights are dimmed to the 
point where they are not visible to the naked eye but they are 
obvious to someone wearing goggles schoel said 
he added fort campbell flies every night with night vision 
goggles its as routine here as driving at night in your car 
