<TEXT>
a shortage of track inspectors has contributed 
to worn railroad switches in csx transportation cos 
baltimorepittsburgh division a federal agency said thursday in an 
audit prompted by a series of freight train accidents 
the federal railroad administration which is part of the 
transportation department said that track along main routes is 
generally in top condition in the division which includes the 
district of columbia and parts of maryland pennsylvania virginia 
west virginia and new york 
but the audit also found that the training equipping and 
numerical strength of the maintenance of way forces in this 
division are inadequate a factor which threatens the companys 
capacity to maintain the quality of its track over the long term 
maintenance of way employees inspect track because manpower 
levels are low the audit said the districts assigned each csx 
track inspector are too large to be covered by a single individual 
inspectors compensate by focusing their efforts on main line track 
which is almost uniformly in excellent condition 
but the tradeoff lies in cursory inspections of turnouts 
or switches that allow a train to move from one track to another 
the audit said the declining condition of these turnouts have 
been a major problem on the line 
worn turnouts or improperly performed track maintenance were 
factors in several of the csx derailments occurring in 1987 the 
audit said 
it said turnouts throughout the division were replete with 
loose adjustable rail braces missing cotter pins and other 
problems the entire gamut of defective turnout conditions 
addressed by fra track standards could be found in one form or 
another in the division it said 
csx in a statement issued from its rail transport group in 
jacksonville fla said it already had begun a retraining program 
taught in part by railroad administration instructors for track 
inspectors foremen road masters and others working on the tracks 
in addition it said it had reached an agreement in the last few 
months with the brotherhood of maintenance of way employees to 
increase the number of people involved in track inspection it 
did not specify how many would be added 
the statement noted that the audit had found a wellmaintained 
signal system and had expressed no overriding concerns about 
the transportation of hazardous materials 
the audit also said the railroad administration detected an 
apparent engineering problem in several sections of csx track 
near confluence pa it added that csx already has begun to 
reconstruct or move switches in the area 
last may a csx chemical tanker train derailed in confluence 
splintering a control tower and killing its operator and forcing 
nearby residents to evacuate it was the third derailment in the 
southwest pennsylvania community in five months 
csx trains also were involved in two derailments last year in 
the washington area in june 21 cars from a 134car train 
derailed temporarily halting subway service from suburban silver 
spring md and takoma park md in september 14 cars on a csx 
train derailed in northeast washington damaging 500 feet of metro 
subway track an electrical power station and a warehouse 
although accidents prompted the audit none were specifically 
addressed in the document as part of the audit more than 1800 
miles of track were inspected last fall 
