rep larry smith on thursday introduced 
resolutions that would deny foreign aid and trade privileges to 
mexico the bahamas peru bolivia and paraguay for alleged failure 
to cooperate with us antidrug efforts 
smith chairman of the house foreign affairs committees task 
force on international narcotics control said the five countries 
were wrongly certified by president reagan on march 1 as 
cooperating with drug enforcement programs 
some of these cooperative countries have even actively 
frustrated our efforts to stop the production of drugs and their 
trafficking into the united states smith dfla told 
reporters its time the president stands up and does more than 
just saying no 
smith and reps benjamin gilman rny and dante fascell 
dfla chairman of the house foreign affairs committee said the 
purpose of the resolutions was not necessarily to cut off aid to 
the five countries but to focus public attention on the 
certification process and determine whether it can be improved 
under comprehensive antidrug legislation enacted in 1986 the 
president must certify annually that major drugproducing and 
shipment countries have fully cooperated with the united 
states or they face loss of a years worth of military and 
economic development aid and us support for international 
development bank loans 
countries that are decertified also may suffer a wide range 
of trade sanctions at the presidents discretion these include a 
50 percent boost in import tariffs abrogation of airline 
agreements loss of us sugar quotas and a halt in preferred us 
customs treatment 
reagan recently certified all the 24 major drug countries as 
fully cooperating with us antidrug efforts except for panama 
afghanistan syria and iran which were decertified and for 
lebanon laos and paraguay which were certified for national 
interests 
under the law congress has 45 business days until may 13 to 
overrule any of reagans recent aid certifications and 30 days 
until april 19 to disapprove of further trade privileges for any 
countries the president certified as fully cooperating 
smith said mexico should be penalized because it is the primary 
source of heroin and marijuana entering the united states and the 
smuggling route for onethird of the cocaine destined for us 
consumption 
he said opium production has increased at least 30 percent and 
eradication has fallen by onethird since 1984 smith said 
laundering of illicit drug profits is extensive and that mexico 
provides safe haven for hundreds of drug traffickers indicted in 
the united states 
smith criticized drug enforcement efforts by the other four 
countries especially the bahamas which he said is the major 
transit point for half the cocaine and marijuana entering the 
united states 
at a hearing that smith headed thursday assistant secretary of 
state elliott abrams said that while we believe that mexico is 
capable of even greater effort against narcotics trafficking we 
also believe that mexican cooperation is substantial and 
justifies the presidents decision to certify mexico 
