<TEXT>
ash and sludge produced by gas scrubbers that 
remove sulfur dioxide at coalfired plants generally does not need 
to be regulated as hazardous waste the environmental protection 
agency said thursday 
however small quantities of waste produced in cleaning boilers 
and purifying water do meet the definitions of hazardous wastes and 
the agency said it will consider whether to bring them under 
hazardous waste regulation 
the conclusions were contained in a report to congress on power 
plant wastes required by 1980 amendments to the federal hazardous 
waste law those amendments exempted such waste from regulation 
until completion of the study epa now has until september to 
decide what wastes if any to regulate as hazardous 
the agency said it would defer studying wastes from oilfired 
plants and coal combustion outside the utility industry 
spokeswoman robin woods said the schedule for those studies had not 
been decided but the agency intended to complete them 
coal plants produce a lot of waste in 1984 about 69 million 
tons of ash and 16 million tons of sludge from smokestack gas 
scrubbers used to remove sulfur dioxide a pollutant that helps 
form acid rain epa said that in the year 2000 ash probably would 
be 120 million tons and scrubber waste 50 million tons 
utilities spend 800 million a year in disposing of the waste at 
2 to 31 a ton and the requirements for handling and disposal 
under hazardous waste regulation would increase that to 70 per ton 
or 37 billion 
ash and sludge may contain small quantities of arsenic barium 
cadmium chromium lead mercury and selenium in general these do 
not leach out of the material in landfills to the extent that would 
make them hazardous though some samples did indicate hazardous 
levels of cadmium and arsenic epa said 
