<TEXT>
intravenous drug addicts appear to be spreading 
aids in the united states at a higher rate than homosexuals whose 
chances of contracting the disease could decline us surgeon 
general c everett koop said thursday 
addressing the first international conference on the global 
impact of aids koop said surveys in the united states indicate 
that male homosexuals have undergone a very serious and positive 
change in behavior to reduce their risk of contracting aids 
we might even expect a decline in the rate of aids reporting 
from this group in a year or so he told about 1000 health 
specialists from 63 countries at londons barbican center the 
threeday conference closed thursday 
by contrast koop said intravenous drug abusers have yet to 
realize they face a high risk of contracting aids from sharing 
bloodcontaminated needles 
over the years weve been singularly unsuccessful in 
penetrating the drugaddicted culture with every other public 
health message we ever had including the one that says stop 
using drugs koop added 
the us official last january predicted a rise but not an 
explosion in the number of aids cases among heterosexuals 
in an interview with the associated press earlier thursday koop 
said public health officials must find some innovative and 
creative ways of reaching drug abusers who now pose the greatest 
risk of spreading aids to the uninfected us population 
i think the major problem that we have in the states is how to 
reach the intravenous drug abuser which class seems to be the one 
that is spreading the disease most rapidly at the present time 
koop said 
according to the centers for disease control in atlanta 63 
percent of the 55167 cases of aids reported in the united states 
have been among male homosexuals or bisexuals 17 percent among 
intravenous drug abusers and 7 percent among those who fall into 
both categories 
koop said health policymakers should consider setting up a pilot 
needleexchange program to determine whether it could cut the rate 
of aids infection among drug abusers who share needles 
under needleexchange programs tried in western europe drug 
addicts can turn in used needles and syringes for free sterile 
equipment there are conflicting opinions on whether such programs 
have slowed the spread of aids 
while stressing he was not proposing such a plan but rather 
supporting those who call for it koop said drug abuse was the 
likeliest way that aquired immune deficiency syndrome could spread 
through the heterosexual population 
the genevabased world health organization and the london school 
of hygiene and tropical medicine organized the conference to assess 
the economic and social impact of the aids epidemic which has 
spread to at least 133 countries 
speakers discussed problems ranging from the aids threat to the 
mining industry of zambia to efforts to prevent the spread of 
infection in british prisons 
aids is a disease in which a virus attacks the bodys immune 
system leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections 
and cancers 
aids is most often transmitted through sexual contact but can 
also be transmitted through transfusions of tainted blood or blood 
products aids can also be passed from mother to child at or before 
birth 
