<TEXT>
a pact allowing japan to retrieve plutonium 
from us nuclear wastes would leave the united states without 
effective control over reprocessing of the hazardous material 
the general accounting office has concluded 
the gao the investigative arm of congress also found fault 
with the agreements provisions to guard against proliferation of 
plutonium the principal element in nuclear weapons and said it 
deprived congress of its oversight function 
opponents of the accord said they had failed to work out a 
compromise with the state department and may move to kill the 
agreement next week 
the accord signed last november gives japan advance permission 
for 30 years to recover plutonium from the fuel the united states 
supplies for its nuclear power plants after it is used 
congressional opponents wanted the united states to have the 
right to review the use of plutonium in any future japanese 
facilities on a casebycase basis and to be able to suspend 
the agreement in a terrorism threat or other national security 
situations 
the congressional foes also sought to have the agreement 
reviewed every five years 
these changes would require renegotiating the terms with japan 
which the state department declined to do said a congressional 
source speaking only on condition of anonymity 
a leading opponent sen alan cranston dcalif said it is 
extremely unfortunate the state department has rejected a 
compromise agreement it is a bad agreement it has serious flaws 
cranston chairman of the senate asia subcommittee called on 
the reagan administration to withdraw the accord otherwise he 
said it faces growing opposition in congress 
the gao report was written by milton socolar a special 
assistant to the us comptroller general and was dated feb 29 
it was obtained thursday 
the report said the agreement does not meet various requirements 
of the atomic energy act it said giving blanket approval to 
japan for reprocessing plutonium would leave the united states 
with no effective control over the life of the proposed agreement 
a us official involved in the negotiations said however the 
safeguard concepts in the pact are adequate and that the 
agreement could be suspended in the event of proliferation or a 
terrorist threat 
the official speaking only if not named said the agreement 
makes sure terrorists cannot get into the facilities 
in december the senate foreign relations committee in an 
unusual move voted 153 to return the pact to president reagan and 
asked that it be renegotiated opponents argued it sets a precedent 
to encourage potentially hazardous trade in plutonium which is a 
potent cancercausing agent 
opponents also complained the plutonium would be shipped over 
alaska and possibly other areas of the united states 
on tuesday the state department said the plutonium would be 
shipped in accordance with rigorous physical protection and 
safety requirements 
a statement issued by the nonproliferation office said planes 
carrying the plutonium soon will be able to fly nonstop from 
europe to japan taking a polar route this would avoid overflights 
of the united states canada or any other country 
the administration is therefore prepared to rule out air 
shipments of plutonium under the agreement from overflying or 
landing in the united states except in the case of aircraft 
emergency the statement said 
under the agreement japan would ship the spent nuclear fuel to 
reprocessing plants in britain or france which would separate 
plutonium from the waste the plutonium then would be shipped back 
to japan by air 
the congressional source said the statement was designed to ease 
the concerns of sen frank h murkowski ralaska but did not 
basically alter the flaws in the agreement 
also the source said richard n perle and frank gaffney 
former defense department officials wrote members of congress 
urging rejection of the agreement as seriously flawed and 
complaining that the pentagon was not permitted to play a 
meaningful role in the negotiations with japan 
fortyfive tons of plutonium could be airlifted from europe to 
japan by the year 2000 under the pact it takes 15 pounds to make a 
bomb 
congress has until april 25 to block the agreement with japan or 
it takes effect 
</TEXT>
