<TEXT>
the stock market crash of last october 
obliterated faith in the usual economic forecasting tools leaving 
forecasters thrashing about in the debris 
theyre still at it wondering if the economic signals mean what 
they used to mean does a red light mean stop or could it 
possibly mean go 
the usual tools and instruments such as the index of leading 
economic indicators proved of little value in foretelling the 
earthquake in securities markets and so the question now is 
whether they can be relied upon at all 
immediately after the crash almost every popular forecaster went 
with his or her emotions and lowered estimates for economic 
activity it was a safe bet they reasoned because crashes always 
led to recessions 
the recession didnt come however impossible to comprehend 
then and still hard to believe socalled consumer confidence 
appeared not to be as badly damaged as they had thought people 
still bought companies still hired 
gradually the forecasters became brave again before the end of 
the year the mass of them had raised their estimates again not as 
high as before but enough to push the likelihood of recession 
further back into 1988 
they were on safe ground because such forecasts werent 
forecasts at all but recognition of what already had occurred car 
sales were strong people continued to take out credit and consumer 
confidence had resumed rising 
by january the evidence was sufficient for most of the breed to 
stick their necks out and declare that the chances of recession 
were growing remote still they said it would be a very dull 
economy in 1988 with little expansion 
no sooner had they braved the fates and showed their courage 
than they were shocked again having recovered from their own 
shock economic historians declared in retrospect that the fourth 
quarter had been stronger than realized 
now the sturdy crew of forecasters was confronted with a 
dilemma if the economy was stronger than had been realized before 
perhaps it might be stronger in the future than had been forecast 
who could be certain 
indeed nobody could be certain what could you believe if you 
couldnt believe the measurements of what had occurred in the past 
you really couldnt understand the present and that left you 
without a stick to measure the future 
in such a predicament it is a wise forecaster who uses both 
hands one to point gamely to the future and the other to wave a 
warning that if on the other hand it was a time for hedging 
the hedge was this the economy would grow but sluggishly the 
consumer would spend but cautiously couples would buy homes but 
carefully cars would sell but slowly credit would expand but 
barely 
now the hedge needs clipping 
there are signs the economy is expanding smartly as indicated 
by a surge in job creation and a jobless rate that fell in february 
to just 57 percent the lowest since july 1979 the use of credit 
is strong car sales rose so sharply in late february that even 
manufacturers and dealers were surprised 
the evidence of economic strength piling up recently makes it 
necessary for forecasters to forecast more often just to keep 
their revisions ahead of the event 
meanwhile deep in the privacy of their own minds it seems safe 
to say there is a gnawing uncertainty among economic forecasters 
regarding their powers 
among the public it seems just as safe to say there is 
conviction rather than uncertainty they are certain that the 
forecasters uncertainty is fully justified 
</TEXT>
