<TEXT>
on the fringes of the multiethnic empire that the 
communists seized from the czars minorities emboldened by mikhail 
s gorbachevs reforms are clamoring for a greater say in their 
future and challenging the dictates of moscow 
in recent weeks armenians by the tens of thousands have marched 
in the streets estonians have massed at a monument in their 
capital and police have locked lithuanian activists in their homes 
to keep them from marking the brief period lithuania was an 
independent country 
in the most dramatic incident some members of two neighboring 
nationalities in the southern caucasus republics have directed 
their hostility not at moscow but at each other 
a rancorous territorial dispute has caused bloodshed injuries 
and deaths involving the armenians and neighboring azeris and some 
fearful azeris natives of the azerbaijan republic have fled their 
homes 
the violence and the palpable swelling of nationalist feelings 
on the soviet periphery pose one of the greatest problems yet for 
general secretary gorbachevs kremlin which is trying to enact 
nationwide standards of discipline and efficiency but also to 
decentralize economic control 
events have also poignantly shown how much the soviet union far 
from being an ethnic melting pot is still the uneasy 
conglomeration of disparate peoples that was dubbed by one 
disapproving 19thcentury visitor to russia adolphe de custine as 
a prison of nations 
in the 70 years of soviet power the moscowbased communist 
party and government have viciously fought centrifugal forces they 
feared might split the country into its ethnic components and the 
current party program adopted in 1986 under gorbachev speaks of a 
single soviet people 
but the soviet union extends from central europe to the far east 
and is peopled by more than 100 ethnic strains and speaking 120 
different languages or dialects they range from the dominant 
russians who make up more than 40 percent of the population of 
2845 million to the aleuts a far northern tribe with fewer than 
500 members 
gorbachev has called the formulation of a comprehensive policy 
to ensure national unity while granting each ethnic group its own 
cultural and linguistic rights the most vital fundamental issue 
of our society 
the unique feature of our culture is that it is 
multiethnic gorbachev said in february nationalism in any 
form is blind attempts at selfisolation lead down a spiritual 
blind alley 
underlining the importance of working out a new policy on 
nationalities gorbachev said the central committee the communist 
partys policymaking body would hold a special plenary session to 
discuss the matter 
the day gorbachev made those remarks feb 18 demonstrations 
began in yerevan the armenian capital to protest the central 
committees refusal to permit the joining of the nagornokarabakh 
region part of azerbaijan since 1923 despite its largely armenian 
population to armenia itself 
the protests swelled with some witnesses claiming that more 
than 1 million people had taken to yerevans streets whatever the 
size the rallies were the largest unsanctioned gatherings in 
soviet history 
some in the crowd proclaimed that the future of the contested 
region that is smaller than the state of delaware will demonstrate 
how gorbachevs entire national reform program is to proceed 
karabakh is a test of perestroika gorbachevs reforms 
declared some of the banners carried by chanting and singing 
armenians 
although in theory and under the 1977 constitution all of the 
countrys nationalities are equal the russians and their slavic 
cousins the ukrainians and byelorussians have a firm hold on the 
actual levers of power 
the ruling politburo shows clearly the extent of slavic 
domination a dozen of its members including gorbachev are slavs 
while only one is not foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze a 
georgian 
despite official rhetoric lauding the equality of nations 
russian preeminence is even enshrined in the soviet national 
anthem whose first stanza begins an unbreakable union of free 
republics has been forged forever by great russia 
the 15 constituent soviet republics have been tightly controlled 
by moscow over the years but gorbachevs drive for greater citizen 
participation plus his campaign for glasnost or openness 
have stirred both hopes and doubts about how far moscow will allow 
ethnic minorities to go 
at the same time gorbachev has ignored the penchant of his 
predecessor leonid i brezhnev to let local elites run the 
economic and social affairs of their republics providing they 
adhered to the dictates of moscow 
it was the replacement by gorbachev of kazakhstans ethnic 
kazakh party chief by a russian that sparked two days of rioting in 
the central asian city of alma ata on dec 1718 1986 in which 
two people were killed and 200 injured 
the recent outbursts involving armenians and azeris may 
strengthen the hand of kremlin conservatives who think gorbachevs 
reforms undermine the traditional submission of distant 
nationalities to the central russian power structure 
the more candid exploration of the legacy of dictator josef v 
stalin promoted by orbachev has also brought calls from baltic 
activists to extend glasnost to cover the forced incorporation of 
latvia lithuania and estonia into the soviet union in 1940 
we want to raise the consciousness of people so they remember 
they have the right to be free said the lithuanian activist 
jadvyga beliauskiene last month as police prevented activists from 
publicly marking the 70th anniversary feb 17 of lithuanias 
declaration of independence 
a group of estonians gathered in tallinn on feb 26 the 70th 
anniversary of estonias declaration of independence from soviet 
russia dissident sources in moscow said 2500 to 3000 people 
attended and official media confirmed the rally took place 
the contested region in azerbaijan shows in microcosm the 
problems faced by the kremlin on a national scale in formulating a 
nationalities policy that takes all pieces of the countrys human 
mosaic into account 
the small region is more than threequarters armenian but has 
residents of 48 other groups 
