<TEXT>
several major newspapers are hoping that putting 
an island of advertising in their sea of stock tables will help 
attract more national advertisers to the medium 
the first ad buyer to participate in the unusual effort is 
national car rental system inc 
the minneapolisbased company said wednesday it would spend 2 
million through the end of the year to put quarterpage ads in what 
is being called a new island position on the first page of the 
stock table sections of 16 newspapers in the nations 20 biggest 
markets 
the ads which will be surrounded on four sides by stock 
quotations will appear a minimum of 26 times starting march 17 in 
each newspaper according to lewis carbone a national marketing 
executive 
a committee of the national advertising bureau a trade 
organization came up with the idea for the unusual ad position 
and along with nationals ad agency chiatday inc persuaded the 
16 newspapers to sell it 
michael davies head of the newspaper bureau panel and editor 
and publisher of the hartford courant said the committee looked at 
a dozen proposals for displaying advertising more distinctively 
before deciding on this approach 
he said the committee wanted to find a way to help an ad message 
stand out without disrupting normal reading patterns 
putting an ad in the stock tables seemed appropriate he said 
because people usually look for individual stock prices rather than 
reading through the entire section this doesnt interrupt the 
flow of reading a page he said 
but some big newspapers turned down the idea 
the new york times rejected it because it would make it too 
hard for the reader to get through the stock tables according to 
spokeswoman nancy nielsen 
the wall street journal also balked bernard t flanagan vice 
president for marketing said the placement would be an 
inconvenience to the reader in a sense we want to make it as 
easy as we can for readers to look up their stock quotes he said 
flanagan said the ad placement also takes prestige away from 
the page 
newspapers have seen their share of national advertising 
spending decline steadily in recent years as national advertisers 
turned to television 
newspapers took in 159 percent of total national ad spending in 
1950 but fell to below 6 percent in 1986 
last year national advertisers spent 35 billion in 
newspapers or about 58 percent of their total spending of 606 
billion according to an estimate by the ad agency mccannerickson 
inc 
but robert zach media director for chiatday said the rising 
cost of television time is making advertisers more receptive to 
alternative ways to reach customers 
davies said he expected other advertisers would take an interest 
in the new ad position and that other newspapers would embrace the 
idea 
