<TEXT>
home mortgage rates fell at the quickest pace 
since 1986 early this year partly because of the broad decline in 
interest rates in the wake of the october stock market crash 
according to the government 
the stock market collapse also played a role in boosting net 
deposits at the nations savings institutions during january for 
the fourth straight month the federal home loan bank board 
reported wednesday 
effective rates on typical 30year fixedrate mortgages for 
singlefamily homes dropped to 105 percent in early february from 
1097 percent in early january rates on the most popular type of 
adjustable rate mortgages those with caps on how much the rate can 
change fell to 874 percent from 898 percent over the same period 
the decline in commitment rates is consistent with the 
softening of mortgage demand that generally occurs during the 
winter months said james barth the bank boards chief economist 
however the recent declines were the sharpest since 
1986and appear to have reflected mainly large deposit 
flowsafter the stock market collapseand an acrosstheboard 
decline in interest rates he said 
mortgage lending by sampls in january declined to the lowest level 
since february 1985 savings institutions lent 131 billion in 
mortgages down more than the usual seasonal dropoff from 217 
billion in december 
contributing to the reduced lending volume was a lingering 
skittishness on the part of potential home buyers following the 
oct 19 collapse in stock prices barth said in a statement 
the spread between fixedrate and adjustablerate mortgages 
narrowed to 176 percent the smallest difference since last 
spring the proportion of mortgages being closed with adjustable 
rates edged down from 65 percent in december to 63 percent a month 
later 
but the popularity of adjustablerate loans remains far higher 
than last spring when they represented 20 to 30 percent of the 
market 
a separate survey of mortgage rates by the federal home loan 
mortgage corp indicated 30year fixedrate mortgages averaged 
985 percent last friday down slightly from 987 percent a week 
earlier and sharply lower than 1061 percent on jan 1 this survey 
does not include addon fees known as points which are included 
in the bank boards averages 
the bank board also said net new deposits at the nations 3135 
federally insured sampls increased by 56 billion in january 
following a 26 billion increase in december that compared with 
net withdrawals of 21 billion in january a year ago 
barth said deposits normally increase from december to january 
but he added nearly half of the most recent improvement 
represented nonseasonal factors undoubtedly the precipitous 
decline in the stock market remains one of these factors 
nervous investors seeking a safe haven for their money 
increased deposits by 62 billion in october and 32 billion in 
november 
the last four months represent a sharp reversal of the trend in 
recent years which has been described as a slowmotion run on 
thrift institutions there were net withdrawals of 33 billion in 
1986 and 137 billion in the first nine months of 1987 
