early contract talks between chrysler corp and 
the united auto workers union could help the company and its 
workers heal their recentlybattered relationship a labor expert 
said 
the fact that both sides appear to be pushing for it reflects 
a desire for some stability said harley shaiken a labor and 
technology expert at the university of california at san diego 
the uaws 140member national chrysler bargaining council 
representing 71700 workers at 49 local unions was to meet here 
today to decide whether to start talks as soon as next month 
uaw president owen bieber in detroit to attend a conference on 
aging work forces said he would urge the council to agree to early 
talks but he declined to comment on possible establishment of an 
earlier strike deadline to accompany early talks 
chryslers threeyear contract expires sept 14 talks usually 
begin in midsummer but chrysler asked to start negotiations after 
its failed attempt to sell its 28000worker acustar inc parts 
subsidiary 
the no 3 automaker last week canceled plans to sell acustar 
because of uaw opposition including threatened plantbyplant 
strikes that could have crippled production chrysler instead 
decided to sell or close four acustar plants within 18 months 
in response to the acustar proposal workers also stopped 
participating in unionmanagement programs critical to improving 
productivity and quality and have not returned because of 
unresolved conflicts with the company uaw leaders said 
uaw vice president marc stepp wanted the council to agree to 
early talks which local union leaders said wednesday could help 
prevent plant closures and movement of work by chrysler to outside 
companies or countries 
im positive our membership would be 100 percent in favor of 
that as long as were talking about jobs they would be more than 
willing said local 1264 official fred obrien at chryslers key 
sterling heights stamping plant 
shaiken said an early settlement also would help chrysler and 
its workers put the acustar conflict behind them and basically 
settle into a pattern for the next few years 
a key issue in the decision was whether chrysler also would 
accept an early strike deadline or insist on a target deadline 
without giving the union the right to strike if no settlement is 
reached 
uaw spokesman peter laarman said the union preferred to 
actually start the clock rather than simply set an artificial 
bargaining deadline 
chrysler chief negotiator anthony st john told the detroit news 
on tuesday that the company did not want an early strike deadline 
but the company would not comment wednesday 
chrysler eventually is expected to agree to the pattern contract 
established last fall at ford motor co and general motors corp 
that includes job protection not included in chryslers present 
contract 
the gm and ford contracts forbid layoffs except when production 
falls because of slow sales make it harder for the companies to 
move production outside the company or country and forbid plant 
closings that were not announced before talks started 
obrien said going to the table early would limit the time 
chrysler has to announce further plant closings and make it easier 
for the union to battle the possible closings of the four acustar 
plants 
chrysler buys the largest percentage of outside parts of any big 
three maker 70 percent compared with 30 percent at gm and about 
50 percent at ford and obrien said workers want to prevent 
further outsourcing 
stepp said he also wants the ford profitsharing formula in the 
next contract ford workers tuesday received profitsharing checks 
averaging more than 3700 from fords industryrecord 1987 profits 
of 46 billion 
chrysler has no profitsharing plan 
