<TEXT>
more than 24 million jobs are expected to be 
created in the united states this year fewer than in 1987 but 
still a very healthy number a business research company said 
thursday 
manufacturers and companies with fewer than 20 employees will 
again be leaders in creating jobs according to dun amp bradstreet 
corp which announced the results of its annual survey of 
employment expectations at 5000 companies 
last year the us economy created about 3 million jobs the 
labor department announced last week that the nations civilian 
unemployment rate fell to 57 percent in february its lowest point 
since 1979 
dun amp bradstreet has predicted in a separate report that the 
jobless rate will average 57 percent this year down from an 
average of 62 percent last year the new jobs will be filled by 
new entrants to the labor force 
the goodsproducing sector aided by a cheaper dollar is likely 
to produce more than 610000 jobs this year the most since 1979 
dun amp bradstreet said 
in contrast the goodsproducing sector lost 180000 jobs in 
1986 and then added 210000 last year as it began to recover the 
company said 
this represents a significant departure from the pattern in 
recent years when job growth was driven largely by the services 
sector joseph w duncan the chief economist said in a news 
release 
the hot spot so to speak in 1988 is going to be the 
industrial midwest reid gearhart a dun amp bradstreet analyst 
said in an interview 
companies with fewer than 20 employees are expected to generate 
35 percent of the new jobs in 1988 even though they make up less 
than 19 percent of total employment the company said 
similarly it said companies with fewer than 100 employees are 
likely to generate just over half of the new jobs in spite of 
making up only a third of the employment 
companies with over 25000 employees are likely to lag again in 
1988 contributing slightly less than 7 percent of new jobs in 
spite of making up 20 percent of employment dun amp bradstreet said 
just over 32 percent of manufacturers in the survey said they 
expected to increase employment the highest of any sector the 
corresponding figures in other sectors were 128 percent in 
agriculture 278 percent in mining 313 percent in construction 
275 percent in transportation and public utilities 301 percent 
in wholesale and retail trade 257 percent in finance insurance 
and real estate 315 percent in services and 255 percent in 
government 
