<TEXT>
after almost 70 years of tallying 
livestock sales at the historic pens of the fort worth stockyards 
the livestock market news service said its reports are headed for 
their last roundup 
government officials have issued daily or weekly reports on 
sales at the pens since around 1920 but said wednesday that so few 
cattle and hogs are sold in the city still nicknamed cowtown that 
regular sales reports will be halted march 31 
the oldest cattle pens in fort worth date to 1887 but as urban 
growth has swallowed the stockyards cattle raisers have turned 
away from the maze of traffic lights and freeways to competing 
auctions in small towns said rick wahrmund statewide director of 
the livestock market news service 
ronnie steen who has been reporting stockyard sales since 1976 
said sales have dropped to between 200 and 300 cattle a week for 
months from an average of about 5000 weekly in 1976 daily 
auctions have long since been replaced with a weekly cattle auction 
on mondays 
we dont have enough cattle to know what the market is 
steen said sales volumes of at least 500 are needed to establish 
clear market trends for farmers ranchers and others who use the 
information 
the us department of agriculture began issuing daily livestock 
reports from the fort worth stockyards around 1920 when annual 
sales regularly topped 6 million cattle 1 million hogs and 400000 
sheep 
