<TEXT>
the two broadest measures of the nations money 
supply fell in late february the federal reserve board reported 
thursday 
the fed said the measure known as m2 fell to a seasonally 
adjusted 29475 billion in the week ended feb 29 from 29531 
billion the previous week 
an even broader measure m3 fell to a seasonally adjusted 
37224 billion from 37244 billion 
the narrowest measure of the money supply m1 fell to a 
seasonally adjusted 7551 billion from a revised 7621 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
in judging its monetary policy the fed has indicated it is 
monitoring the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates it also has 
shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply 
measures 
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for 
m2 and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent which is slightly 
lower than the 1987 target of 55 percent to 85 percent the fed 
has not set a specific target range for m1 since early 1987 
in other reports 
the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and 
industrial loans at major new york city banks rose 13 billion 
compared with a decline of 107 billion a week earlier 
the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal 
reserve system at the discount window averaged 378 million a day 
in the week ended wednesday up from 187 million a day in the 
previous week 
the federal reserve said net free reserves averaged 615 
million in the latest twoweek period down from a revised 879 
million in the previous twoweek period 
the federal reserve bank of st louis reported that the 
monetary base the seasonally adjusted total of member bank 
reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and 
in circulation was 2712 billion in the twoweek period ended 
wednesday down from 2724 billion two weeks earlier 
</TEXT>
